<h2>Previous Years</h2>
<pre>In the FIRST Robotics Competition of 2011, MorTorq competed in “Logo Motion”. The objective
of this game was to place inner tubes that were shaped like the triangle, circle, and square of the FIRST
logo onto racks to win points and in the endgame to have smaller robots climb a tower.

In 2010, Breakaway was the name of the game for the FRC. Robots were supposed to be built so
that they could drive over bumps in the field, go through a tunnel/suspend themselves and other robots
on towers, and direct soccer balls into goals.

In 2009, Lunacy was the game for the FRC. The objective of the game was to score as many
game pieces as possible into the opposing side’s trailer in the time allotted.

In 2008, FIRST Overdrive was the name of the game for the FRC. Teams would attempt to do
laps around a central barrier while trying to manipulate “trackballs” over and under overpasses to win
additional points.

In 2007, Rack 'n Roll was the name of the FRC game. The objective of the game was to have two
alliances of three teams each to attempt to arrange inflatable game pieces shaped like toroidals on “The
Rack”, which was a large device with three levels of hanging metal bars on it to place the game pieces
on.

In 2006, Aim High was the title of the game for the FRC of that year. In Aim High alliances would
try and score points by getting balls into goals and arranging their robots into certain positions on the
playing field.

In 2005, Triple Play was the name of the game for the FRC. The objective of the game was to
place the game pieces, Tetras, on the larger goals in an attempt to create rows of three which was made
by having a Tetra with your alliance’s color on the highest point of the goal.</pre>

